<subSubSection id="C30FB2903527FFEBFF47FE40FA8FFE0C" pageId="4" pageNumber="360" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="8BAAE11B3527FFEBFF47FE40FA8FFE0C" blockId="4.[151,1437,253,1108]" pageId="4" pageNumber="360">
<emphasis id="B9613D093527FFEBFF47FE40FEE1FE30" bold="true" box="[199,334,434,460]" pageId="4" pageNumber="360">Etymology.</emphasis>
The epithet honors an extinct indigenous civilization from the Andean region of 
<collectingCountry id="F302A18B3527FFEBFB5BFE40FAE3FE30" box="[1243,1356,434,460]" name="Colombia" pageId="4" pageNumber="360">Colombia</collectingCountry>
, which inhabited the 
<collectingRegion id="49D12FF93527FFEBFEB0FE24FED0FE0C" box="[304,383,470,496]" country="Colombia" name="Caldas" pageId="4" pageNumber="360">Caldas</collectingRegion>
, north of 
<collectingRegion id="49D12FF93527FFEBFE6AFE24FD33FE0C" box="[490,668,470,496]" country="Colombia" name="Valle del Cauca" pageId="4" pageNumber="360">Valle del Cauca</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingRegion id="49D12FF93527FFEBFD27FE24FCACFE0C" box="[679,771,470,496]" country="Colombia" name="Quindio" pageId="4" pageNumber="360">Quindío</collectingRegion>
and 
<collectingRegion id="49D12FF93527FFEBFCBAFE24FC0BFE0C" box="[826,932,470,496]" country="Colombia" name="Risaralda" pageId="4" pageNumber="360">Risaralda</collectingRegion>
departments. Noun in apposition.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C30FB2903527FFEBFF47FE0BFCE0FD58" pageId="4" pageNumber="360" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8BAAE11B3527FFEBFF47FE0BFCE0FD58" blockId="4.[151,1437,253,1108]" pageId="4" pageNumber="360">
<emphasis id="B9613D093527FFEBFF47FE0BFEEDFDEF" bold="true" box="[199,322,505,531]" pageId="4" pageNumber="360">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Males of 
<taxonomicName id="4C159A983527FFEBFE2EFE09FD97FDE8" authority="Muñoz-Charry &amp; Galvis &amp; Martínez, 2022" authorityName="Muñoz-Charry &amp; Galvis &amp; Martínez" authorityYear="2022" box="[430,568,506,532]" class="Arachnida" family="Salticidae" genus="Lapsias" kingdom="Animalia" order="Araneae" pageId="4" pageNumber="360" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="quimbaya" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis id="B9613D093527FFEBFE2EFE09FD97FDE8" box="[430,568,506,532]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="360">L. quimbaya</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis id="B9613D093527FFEBFDBEFE08FD39FDE8" bold="true" box="[574,662,506,532]" pageId="4" pageNumber="360">
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A25280723527FFEBFDBEFE08FD39FDE8" box="[574,662,506,532]" pageId="4" pageNumber="360" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
can be recognized from those of the remaining species in the genus by their rounded bulb, the long embolus (e) that is projected prolaterally and dorsally, with the final portion returning ventrally in front of the cymbium tip, the long and slender median apophysis (ma) that extends over the embolus base, the tibia with a large dorsal apophysis (dTa) and the retrolateral apophysis (RTA), both projected dorsally (
<figureCitation id="132EFD9E3527FFEBFAEBFD94FF7DFD58" captionStart="FIGURES 8–11" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1915,1939]" captionTargetBox="[152,1435,248,1875]" captionTargetId="figure-55@3.[151,1436,237,1892]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 8–11. L. quimbaya sp. nov., male holotype (ICN-Ar 9217), 8 habitus; 9 left palp, ventral view; 10 same, retrolateral view; 11 same, prolateral view.Abbreviations: dTa= dorsal tibial apophysis, e=embolus, ma=median apophysis, RTA=retrolateral tibial apophysis, sd=sperm duct. Scale bars = 0.5 mm (8), 0.20 (9–11)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6501130" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6501130/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="360">Figs 9–11</figureCitation>
). This is also one of the smallest 
<taxonomicName id="4C159A983527FFEBFDC5FD79FD5BFD58" box="[581,756,650,676]" pageId="4" pageNumber="360">
<emphasis id="B9613D093527FFEBFDC5FD79FD33FD58" box="[581,668,651,676]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="360">Lapsias</emphasis>
species
</taxonomicName>
known.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C30FB2903527FFEBFF47FD5FFE0DFBF0" pageId="4" pageNumber="360" type="description">
<paragraph id="8BAAE11B3527FFEBFF47FD5FFCDBFC14" blockId="4.[151,1437,253,1108]" pageId="4" pageNumber="360">
<emphasis id="B9613D093527FFEBFF47FD5FFD8BFD3B" bold="true" box="[199,548,685,712]" pageId="4" pageNumber="360">
Description. Male (
<typeStatus id="54AE5FB93527FFEBFE2CFD5FFDB7FD3B" box="[428,536,685,711]" pageId="4" pageNumber="360">holotype</typeStatus>
).
</emphasis>
Total length: 2.90. Carapace light brown, 1.49 long, 1.23 wide, 0.95 high (
<figureCitation id="132EFD9E3527FFEBFAEFFD5CFF08FD10" captionStart="FIGURES 8–11" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1915,1939]" captionTargetBox="[152,1435,248,1875]" captionTargetId="figure-55@3.[151,1436,237,1892]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 8–11. L. quimbaya sp. nov., male holotype (ICN-Ar 9217), 8 habitus; 9 left palp, ventral view; 10 same, retrolateral view; 11 same, prolateral view.Abbreviations: dTa= dorsal tibial apophysis, e=embolus, ma=median apophysis, RTA=retrolateral tibial apophysis, sd=sperm duct. Scale bars = 0.5 mm (8), 0.20 (9–11)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6501130" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6501130/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="360">Fig. 8</figureCitation>
). OC dark brown, 0.80 long. Anterior eye row 1.26 wide and posterior 1.21 wide. Sternum yellowish, 0.61 long, 0.57 wide. Labium yellowish, 0.23 long, 0.22 wide. Chelicerae brown, with two retromarginal and two promarginal teeth. Palp brown, rounded bulb with a long embolus (e) projected dorsally, membranous and slender median apophysis (ma), tibia with a long dorsal apophysis (dTa) and a retrolateral apophysis (RTA), both projected dorsally (
<figureCitation id="132EFD9E3527FFEBFF1FFC90FEBCFC80" box="[159,275,866,892]" captionStart="FIGURES 8–11" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1915,1939]" captionTargetBox="[152,1435,248,1875]" captionTargetId="figure-55@3.[151,1436,237,1892]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 8–11. L. quimbaya sp. nov., male holotype (ICN-Ar 9217), 8 habitus; 9 left palp, ventral view; 10 same, retrolateral view; 11 same, prolateral view.Abbreviations: dTa= dorsal tibial apophysis, e=embolus, ma=median apophysis, RTA=retrolateral tibial apophysis, sd=sperm duct. Scale bars = 0.5 mm (8), 0.20 (9–11)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6501130" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6501130/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="360">Figs 9–11</figureCitation>
). Leg formula: 4132, all dark brown with yellow marks. Leg macrosetae: femur, I d 1 di; II d 2 di; III p 1 di; patella, III–IV p 1 me, r 1 me; tibia, I v 2-2-2; II v 1-1-1, p 0-1-1; III v 1-1-2, r 1-1; IV v 1-0-2, p 1-1, r 1-1; metatarsus, I v 2-2; II p 1-1-2, r 1-0-2; III v 1 di, p 2-0-2, r 2-0-2; IV v 1-0-2, p 1-0-2, r 1-0-2. Abdomen light yellow with dark brown spots and posteromedial chevron marks (
<figureCitation id="132EFD9E3527FFEBFCA2FC3CFCC9FC14" box="[802,870,974,1000]" captionStart="FIGURES 8–11" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1915,1939]" captionTargetBox="[152,1435,248,1875]" captionTargetId="figure-55@3.[151,1436,237,1892]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 8–11. L. quimbaya sp. nov., male holotype (ICN-Ar 9217), 8 habitus; 9 left palp, ventral view; 10 same, retrolateral view; 11 same, prolateral view.Abbreviations: dTa= dorsal tibial apophysis, e=embolus, ma=median apophysis, RTA=retrolateral tibial apophysis, sd=sperm duct. Scale bars = 0.5 mm (8), 0.20 (9–11)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6501130" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6501130/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="360">Fig. 8</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BAAE11B3527FFEBFF47FC00FE0DFBF0" blockId="4.[151,1437,253,1108]" box="[199,418,1010,1036]" pageId="4" pageNumber="360">
<emphasis id="B9613D093527FFEBFF47FC00FE8AFBF0" bold="true" box="[199,293,1010,1036]" pageId="4" pageNumber="360">Female.</emphasis>
Unknown.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C30FB2903527FFEBFF47FBE7FAF4FBA8" pageId="4" pageNumber="360" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="8BAAE11B3527FFEBFF47FBE7FAF4FBA8" blockId="4.[151,1437,253,1108]" pageId="4" pageNumber="360">
<emphasis id="B9613D093527FFEBFF47FBE7FD89FBD3" bold="true" box="[199,550,1045,1072]" pageId="4" pageNumber="360">Distribution and Comments.</emphasis>
Known only from its type locality in the Colombian Andes (
<figureCitation id="132EFD9E3527FFEBFA80FBE4FAF6FBCD" box="[1280,1369,1046,1073]" captionStart="FIGURE 57" captionStartId="15.[151,250,1890,1914]" captionTargetBox="[164,1423,181,1866]" captionTargetId="figure-22@15.[164,1423,181,1866]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="FIGURE 57. Distribution of jumping spiders of the tribe Lapsiini Maddison (Salticidae: Spartaeinae) in South America. The figures with a dot inside represent the type species of each genus." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6501154" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6501154/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="360">Fig. 57</figureCitation>
). The 
<typeStatus id="54AE5FB93527FFEBFF17FBC8FF56FBA8" box="[151,249,1082,1108]" pageId="4" pageNumber="360">holotype</typeStatus>
male was collected in a well-conserved Andean moist forest, beating low vegetation during the day.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
</treatment>
